1. Explain linux file permissions
A: read - r - 4
   write - w - 2
   execte - x - 1
   Owner -- group -- others

2. Diff between 755, 644,777
A: 755 --> rwx--rx-rx
   644 --> rw--r--r
   777 --> rwx--rwx--rwx ( we never use 777 in production unless its really necessary)

3. Diff between chmod,chown, chgrp
A: chmod --> changes file permissions --> chmod 755 file_name
   chown --> changes file owner --> chown ubuntu file.txt
   chgrp --> changes file group --> chgrp developers file.txt

4. Express symbolic and numeric permissions
A: numeric : chmod 744 file.txt
   symbolic: chmod u+x app.sh ( gives owner execute permission)
             chmod g-w app.sh ( remove write permission from group)
          u --> user/owner | g --> group | o --> others

5. How do you recursively change permissions
A: chmod -R 755 file.txt

6. Diff between file and directory permissions
A: Files:
    read --> view contents
    write --> modifies the file
    execute --> run the file
  Directories:
    read --> list files
    write --> create / delete files
    execute --> enter directory (cd)

7. How to create a new user, how to add a user to group
A: to create user: sudo adduser aishu
   to add user to group: sudo usermod -aG group1 aishu
    verify : groups aishu ( tells aishu user is in which groups)

8. How to lock and unlock a user?
A: to immediately disable access for user we lock them, when we lock a ! is added to the password by linux so when user tries to login it shows password error so
    they cant login
   sudo passwd -l aishu --> lock username
   sudo passwd -u aishu --> unlocks username

9. check who is currently logged in
A: who OR w OR last

-----------------
PRODUCTION TROUBLESHOOTING

1. A user cannot edit a file, how do you troubleshoot?
A: check ownership: ls -l file.txt (ls only gives file name, -l gives detailed info of file like permissions)
   to get more data about permissions of the file(more than -l) : stat file.txt
   check user's groups: groups username
   to see additional permissions (ACL's): getfact file_name.txt
   modify permissions if necessary

2. Application says permission denied
A: check ownership : ls -l
   check if its missing execute permissions

3. script works manually but fails in cron
A: check execute permission : chmod +x file.txt
   write absolute paths:
      wrong: python backup.py
      right: /usr/bin/python3 /home/ubuntu/backup.py (write like this)

4. User cannot SSH into server
A: check ssh status : systemctl status ssh
   check permissions: ls -l ~/.ssh
   correct permissions: chmod 600 ~/.ssh
   check logs: sudo tail -f /var/log/auth.log

5. Developer cannot deploy application
A: check ownership: ls -ld /var/www/hmtl (-ld means show details of folder or directory not the files inside it)
   check permission: ls -l /var/www/html

6. User suddenly lost access to shared folder
A: check permission: ls -ld /shared
   check ownership : stat shared
   check groups: groups shared
   check ACL : getfact /shared

7. Permission denied after deployment
A: new deployment changed ownership or application running under another user.

8. Application cannot write logs
A: check: ls -ls /var/log/app
   check :df -h /var/log/app

9. Developer accidently executed chmod -R 777 /
A: restore permission from backup or rebuild server if the permission cannot be trusted anymore

10. A file was accidently deleted, can linux recover it?
A: Normally linux doesnt provide recycle bin for deleted files but we can restore from backup or snapshots.

11. what is umask?
A: It defines the default permissions assigned to newly created files and directories.

12. what is ACL's?
A: these are special permissions that we can specify to user or group. this gives more options compared to standard rwx permissions

13. what is suid?
A: SUID allows a file to execute with the permissions of its owner.
   You will notice an s instead of x in the owner's execute position.

14. what is SGID?
A: On directories, SGID ensures that newly created files inherit the directory's group instead of the creator's primary group.
   Useful for shared project directories.

15. what is sticky bit?
A: Commonly used on shared directories like /tmp.

